# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: enzyme
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:enzyme/acetolactate-decarboxylase] Hence, this enzyme has one substrate, (S)-2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoate, and two products, (R)-2-acetoin and CO2.
[src:enzyme/acetolactate-decarboxylase] This enzyme belongs to the family of lyases, specifically the carboxy-lyases, which cleave carbon-carbon bonds.
[src:enzyme/acetolactate-decarboxylase] The systematic name of this enzyme class is **(S)-2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoate carboxy-lyase [(R)-2-acetoin-forming]**.
[src:enzyme/acetolactate-decarboxylase] Other names in common use include **alpha-acetolactate decarboxylase**, and **(S)-2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoate carboxy-lyase**.
[src:enzyme/acetolactate-decarboxylase] This enzyme participates in butanoate metabolism and c5-branched dibasic acid metabolism.
[src:enzyme/acetolactate-decarboxylase] Alpha Acetolactate Decarboxylase (ALDC), sold as Brewzyme-D, is used in brewing beer to limit the formation of 'diacetyl'.
[src:enzyme/acetolactate-decarboxylase] As of late 2007, only one structure has been solved for this class of enzymes, with the PDB accession code PDB: 1XV2.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It is found at mainly neuromuscular junctions and in chemical synapses of the cholinergic type, where its activity serves to terminate cholinergic synaptic transmission.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It belongs to the carboxylesterase family of enzymes.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It is the primary target of inhibition by organophosphorus compounds such as nerve agents and pesticides.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] AChE is a hydrolase that hydrolyzes choline esters.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It has a very high catalytic activity—each molecule of AChE degrades about 5,000 molecules of acetylcholine (ACh) per second, approaching the limit allowed by diffusion of the substrate.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The active site of AChE comprises two subsites—the anionic site and the esteratic subsite.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The structure and mechanism of action of AChE have been elucidated from the crystal structure of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The anionic subsite accommodates the positive quaternary amine of acetylcholine as well as other cationic substrates and inhibitors.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The cationic substrates are not bound by a negatively charged amino acid in the anionic site, but by interaction of 14 aromatic residues that line a gorge leading to the active site.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] All 14 amino acids in the aromatic gorge are highly conserved across different species.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Among the aromatic amino acids, tryptophan 84 is critical and its substitution with alanine results in a 3000-fold decrease in reactivity.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The gorge is approximately 20 angstroms deep and five angstroms wide.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The esteratic subsite, where acetylcholine is hydrolyzed to acetate and choline, contains the catalytic triad of three amino acids: serine 203, histidine 447 and glutamate 334.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] These three amino acids are similar to the triad in other serine proteases except that the glutamate is the third member rather than aspartate.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Moreover, the triad is of opposite chirality to that of other proteases.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The hydrolysis reaction of the carboxyl ester leads to the formation of an acyl-enzyme and free choline.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Then, the acyl-enzyme undergoes nucleophilic attack by a water molecule, assisted by the histidine 440 group, liberating acetic acid and regenerating the free enzyme.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] AChE is found in many biological species, including humans and other mammals, invertebrates, and plants.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] In humans, AChE is a cholinergic enzyme involved in the hydrolysis of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine (ACh) into its constituents, choline, and acetate.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Overall, in mammals, AChE is primarily involved in the termination of impulse transmission at cholinergic synapses by rapid hydrolysis of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] In invertebrates, AChE plays a similar role in nerve conduction processes at the neuromuscular junction.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It is usually located in the membranes of these animals and controls ionic currents in excitable membranes.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] In plants, the biological functions of AChE are less clear, and its existence has been recognized by indirect evidence of its activity.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] For instance, a study on Solanum lycopersicum (tomato) identified 87 SlAChE genes containing GDSL lipase/acylhydrolase domain.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The study also showed up-and down-regulation of SlAChE genes under salinity stress condition.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Some marine fungi have been found to produce compounds that inhibit AChE.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] However, the specific role and mechanisms of AChE in fungi are not as well-studied as in mammals.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The presence and role of AChE in bacteria is not well-documented.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] During neurotransmission, ACh is released from the presynaptic neuron into the synaptic cleft and binds to ACh receptors on the post-synaptic membrane, relaying the signal from the nerve.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] AChE is concentrated in the synaptic cleft, where it terminates the signal transmission by hydrolyzing ACh.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The liberated choline is taken up again by the pre-synaptic neuron and ACh is synthesized by combining with acetyl-CoA through the action of choline acetyltransferase.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] A cholinomimetic drug disrupts this process by acting as a cholinergic neurotransmitter that is impervious to acetylcholinesterase's lysing action.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Drugs or toxins that inhibit AChE lead to persistence of high concentrations of ACh within synapses, leading to increased cholinergic signaling within the central nervous system, autonomic ganglia and neuromuscular junctions.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Irreversible inhibitors of AChE may lead to muscular paralysis, convulsions, bronchial constriction, and death by asphyxiation.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Organophosphates (OP), esters of phosphoric acid, are a class of irreversible AChE inhibitors.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Cleavage of OP by AChE leaves a phosphoryl group in the esteratic site, which is slow to be hydrolyzed (on the order of days) and can become covalently bound.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Irreversible AChE inhibitors have been used in insecticides (e.g., malathion) and nerve gases for chemical warfare (e.g., Sarin and VX).
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Carbamates, esters of N-methyl carbamic acid, are AChE inhibitors that hydrolyze in hours and have been used for medical purposes (e.g., physostigmine for the treatment of glaucoma).
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Reversible inhibitors occupy the esteratic site for short periods of time (seconds to minutes) and are used to treat of a range of central nervous system diseases.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Tetrahydroaminoacridine (THA) and donepezil are FDA-approved to improve cognitive function in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Rivastigmine is also used to treat Alzheimer's and Lewy body dementia, and pyridostigmine bromide is used to treat myasthenia gravis.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] An endogenous inhibitor of AChE in neurons is Mir-132 microRNA, which may limit inflammation in the brain by silencing the expression of this protein and allowing ACh to act in an anti-inflammatory capacity.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It has also been shown that the main active ingredient in cannabis, tetrahydrocannabinol, is a competitive inhibitor of acetylcholinesterase.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] AChE is found in many types of conducting tissue: nerve and muscle, central and peripheral tissues, motor and sensory fibers, and cholinergic and noncholinergic fibers.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The activity of AChE is higher in motor neurons than in sensory neurons.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Acetylcholinesterase is also found on the red blood cell membranes, where different forms constitute the Yt blood group antigens.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Acetylcholinesterase exists in multiple molecular forms, which possess similar catalytic properties, but differ in their oligomeric assembly and mode of attachment to the cell surface.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] In mammals, acetylcholinesterase is encoded by a single AChE gene while some invertebrates have multiple acetylcholinesterase genes.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Note higher vertebrates also encode a closely related paralog BCHE (butyrylcholinesterase) with 50% amino acid identity to ACHE.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Diversity in the transcribed products from the sole mammalian gene arises from alternative mRNA splicing and post-translational associations of catalytic and structural subunits.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] There are three known forms: T (tail), R (read through), and H (hydrophobic).
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The major form of acetylcholinesterase found in brain, muscle, and other tissues, known as is the hydrophilic species, which forms disulfide-linked oligomers with collagenous, or lipid-containing structural subunits.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] In the neuromuscular junctions AChE expresses in asymmetric form which associates with ColQ or subunit.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] In the central nervous system it is associated with PRiMA which stands for Proline Rich Membrane anchor to form symmetric form.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] In either case, the ColQ or PRiMA anchor serves to maintain the enzyme in the intercellular junction, ColQ for the neuromuscular junction and PRiMA for synapses.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The other, alternatively spliced form expressed primarily in the erythroid tissues, differs at the C-terminus, and contains a cleavable hydrophobic peptide with a PI-anchor site.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It associates with membranes through the phosphoinositide (PI) moieties added post-translationally.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The third type has, so far, only been found in *Torpedo* sp. and mice although it is hypothesized in other species.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] It is thought to be involved in the stress response and, possibly, inflammation.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] The nomenclatural variations of ACHE and of cholinesterases generally are discussed at *Cholinesterase § Types and nomenclature*.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] For acetylcholine esterase (AChE), **reversible inhibitors** are those that do not irreversibly bond to and deactivate AChE.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Drugs that reversibly inhibit acetylcholine esterase are being explored as treatments for Alzheimer's disease and myasthenia gravis, among others.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Exposure to acetylcholinesterase inhibitors is one of several studied explanations for the chronic cognitive symptoms veterans displayed after returning from the Gulf War.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Soldiers were dosed with AChEI pyridostigmine bromide (PB) as protection from nerve agent weapons.
[src:enzyme/acetylcholinesterase] Studying acetylcholine levels using microdialysis and HPLC-ECD, researchers at the University of South Carolina School of Medicine determined PB, when combined with a stress element can lead to cognitive responses.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius model of reaction rates, **activation energy** is the minimum amount of energy that must be available to reactants for a chemical reaction to occur.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The activation energy (*E*a) of a reaction is measured in kilojoules per mole (kJ/mol) or kilocalories per mole (kcal/mol).
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Activation energy is the minimum energy barrier that reactant molecules must overcome to transform into products.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] A reaction occurs only if enough molecules have kinetic energy equal to or greater than this barrier, which usually requires sufficiently high temperature.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The term "activation energy" was introduced in 1889 by the Swedish scientist Svante Arrhenius.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Although less commonly used, activation energy also applies to nuclear reactions and various other physical phenomena.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The Arrhenius equation gives the quantitative basis of the relationship between the activation energy and the rate at which a reaction proceeds.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] where *A* is the pre-exponential factor for the reaction, *R* is the universal gas constant, *T* is the absolute temperature (usually in kelvins), and *k* is the reaction rate coefficient.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Even without knowing *A*, *E*a can be evaluated from the variation in reaction rate coefficients as a function of temperature (within the validity of the Arrhenius equation).
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] At a more advanced level, the net Arrhenius activation energy term from the Arrhenius equation is best regarded as an experimentally determined parameter that indicates the sensitivity of the reaction rate to temperature.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] There are two objections to associating this activation energy with the threshold barrier for an elementary reaction.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] First, it is often unclear as to whether or not reaction does proceed in one step; threshold barriers that are averaged out over all elementary steps have little theoretical value.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] A substance that modifies the transition state to lower the activation energy is termed a catalyst; a catalyst composed only of protein and (if applicable) small molecule cofactors is termed an enzyme.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] A catalyst increases the rate of reaction without being consumed in the reaction.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In addition, the catalyst lowers the activation energy, but it does not change the energies of the original reactants or products, and so does not change equilibrium.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Rather, the reactant energy and the product energy remain the same and only the *activation energy* is altered (lowered).
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] A catalyst is able to reduce the activation energy by forming a transition state in a more favorable manner.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Catalysts, by nature, create a more "comfortable" fit for the substrate of a reaction to progress to a transition state.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] This is possible due to a release of energy that occurs when the substrate binds to the active site of a catalyst.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Upon binding to a catalyst, substrates partake in numerous stabilizing forces while within the active site (e.g. hydrogen bonding or van der Waals forces).
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Specific and favorable bonding occurs within the active site until the substrate forms to become the high-energy transition state.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Forming the transition state is more favorable with the catalyst because the favorable stabilizing interactions within the active site *release* energy.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] A chemical reaction is able to manufacture a high-energy transition state molecule more readily when there is a stabilizing fit within the active site of a catalyst.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The binding energy of a reaction is this energy released when favorable interactions between substrate and catalyst occur.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The binding energy released assists in achieving the unstable transition state.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Reactions without catalysts need a higher input of energy to achieve the transition state.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Non-catalyzed reactions do not have free energy available from active site stabilizing interactions, such as catalytic enzyme reactions.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius equation, the term activation energy (*E*a) is used to describe the energy required to reach the transition state, and the exponential relationship *k* = *A* exp(−*E*a/*RT*) holds.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In transition state theory, a more sophisticated model of the relationship between reaction rates and the transition state, a superficially similar mathematical relationship, the Eyring equation, is used to describe the rate constant of a reaction: *k* = (*k*B*T* / *h*) exp(−Δ*G*‡ / *RT*).
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] However, instead of modeling the temperature dependence of reaction rate phenomenologically, the Eyring equation models individual elementary steps of a reaction.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Thus, for a multistep process, there is no straightforward relationship between the two models.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Nevertheless, the functional forms of the Arrhenius and Eyring equations are similar, and for a one-step process, simple and chemically meaningful correspondences can be drawn between Arrhenius and Eyring parameters.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Instead of also using *E*a, the Eyring equation uses the concept of Gibbs energy and the symbol Δ*G*‡ to denote the Gibbs energy of activation to achieve the transition state.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In the equation, *k*B and *h* are the Boltzmann and Planck constants, respectively.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Although the equations look similar, the Gibbs energy contains an entropic term in addition to the enthalpic one.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius equation, this entropic term is accounted for by the pre-exponential factor *A*.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] More specifically, we can write the Gibbs free energy of activation in terms of enthalpy and entropy of activation: Δ*G*‡ = Δ*H*‡ − *T* Δ*S*‡.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Then, for a unimolecular, one-step reaction, the *approximate* relationships *E*a = Δ*H*‡ + *RT* and *A* = (*k*B*T*/*h*) exp(1 + Δ*S*‡/*R*) hold.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Note, however, that in Arrhenius theory proper, *A* is temperature independent, while here, there is a linear dependence on *T*.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] For a one-step unimolecular process whose half-life at room temperature is about 2 hours, Δ*G*‡ is approximately 23 kcal/mol.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] This is also the roughly the magnitude of *E*a for a reaction that proceeds over several hours at room temperature.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Due to the relatively small magnitude of *T*Δ*S*‡ and *RT* at ordinary temperatures for most reactions, in sloppy discourse, *E*a, Δ*G*‡, and Δ*H*‡ are often conflated and all referred to as the "activation energy".
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The enthalpy, entropy and Gibbs energy of activation are more correctly written as Δ‡*H*o, Δ‡*S*o and Δ‡*G*o respectively, where the o indicates a quantity evaluated between standard states.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] However, some authors omit the o in order to simplify the notation.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The total free energy change of a reaction is independent of the activation energy however.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Physical and chemical reactions can be either exergonic or endergonic, but the activation energy is not related to the spontaneity of a reaction.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The overall reaction energy change is not altered by the activation energy.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In some cases, rates of reaction *decrease* with increasing temperature.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] When following an approximately exponential relationship so the rate constant can still be fit to an Arrhenius expression, this results in a negative value of *E*a.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Elementary reactions exhibiting negative activation energies are typically barrierless reactions, in which the reaction proceeding relies on the capture of the molecules in a potential well.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Such a situation no longer leads itself to direct interpretations as the height of a potential barrier.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Some multistep reactions can also have apparent negative activation energies.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] For example, the overall rate constant k for a two-step reaction A ⇌ B, B → C is given by k = k2K1, where k2 is the rate constant of the rate-limiting slow second step and K1 is the equilibrium constant of the rapid first step.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] In some reactions, K1 decreases with temperature more rapidly than k2 increases, so that k actually decreases with temperature corresponding to a negative observed activation energy.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] An example is the oxidation of nitric oxide which is a termolecular reaction ${\ce {2 NO + O2 -> 2 NO2}}$ .
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] Certain cationic polymerization reactions have negative activation energies so that the rate decreases with temperature.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] For chain-growth polymerization, the overall activation energy is $\textstyle E=E_{i}+E_{p}-E_{t}$ , where i, p and t refer respectively to initiation, propagation and termination steps.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The propagation step normally has a very small activation energy, so that the overall value is negative if the activation energy for termination is larger than that for initiation.
[src:enzyme/activation-energy] The normal range of overall activation energies for cationic polymerization varies from 40 to 60 kJ/mol.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In biology and biochemistry, the **active site** is the region of an enzyme where substrate molecules bind and undergo a chemical reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The active site consists of amino acid residues that form temporary bonds with the substrate, the *binding site*, and residues that catalyse a reaction of that substrate, the ***catalytic site***.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Although the active site occupies only ~10–20% of the volume of an enzyme, it is the most important part as it directly catalyzes the chemical reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It usually consists of three to four amino acids, while other amino acids within the protein are required to maintain the tertiary structure of the enzymes.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Each active site is evolved to be optimised to bind a particular substrate and catalyse a particular reaction, resulting in high specificity.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This specificity is determined by the arrangement of amino acids within the active site and the structure of the substrates.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Sometimes enzymes also need to bind with some cofactors to fulfil their function.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The active site is usually a groove or pocket of the enzyme which can be located in a deep tunnel within the enzyme, or between the interfaces of multimeric enzymes.
[src:enzyme/active-site] An active site can catalyse a reaction repeatedly as residues are not altered at the end of the reaction (they may change during the reaction, but are regenerated by the end).
[src:enzyme/active-site] This process is achieved by lowering the activation energy of the reaction, so more substrates have enough energy to undergo reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Usually, an enzyme molecule has only one active site, and the active site fits with one specific type of substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] An active site contains a binding site that binds the substrate and orients it for catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The orientation of the substrate and the close proximity between it and the active site is so important that in some cases the enzyme can still function properly even though all other parts are mutated and lose function.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Initially, the interaction between the active site and the substrate is non-covalent and transient.
[src:enzyme/active-site] There are four important types of interaction that hold the substrate in a defined orientation and form an enzyme-substrate complex (ES complex): hydrogen bonds, van der Waals interactions, hydrophobic interactions and electrostatic force interactions.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The charge distribution on the substrate and active site must be complementary, which means all positive and negative charges must be cancelled out.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Otherwise, there will be a repulsive force pushing them apart.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The active site usually contains non-polar amino acids, although sometimes polar amino acids may also occur.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The binding of substrate to the binding site requires at least three contact points in order to achieve stereo-, regio-, and enantioselectivity.
[src:enzyme/active-site] For example, alcohol dehydrogenase which catalyses the transfer of a hydride ion from ethanol to NAD+ interacts with the substrate methyl group, hydroxyl group and the pro-*(R)* hydrogen that will be abstracted during the reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In order to exert their function, enzymes need to assume their correct protein fold (*native fold*) and tertiary structure.
[src:enzyme/active-site] To maintain this defined three-dimensional structure, proteins rely on various types of interactions between their amino acid residues.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If these interactions are interfered with, for example by extreme pH values, high temperature or high ion concentrations, this will cause the enzyme to denature and lose its catalytic activity.
[src:enzyme/active-site] A tighter fit between an active site and the substrate molecule is believed to increase the efficiency of a reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If the tightness between the active site of DNA polymerase and its substrate is increased, the fidelity, which means the correct rate of DNA replication will also increase.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Most enzymes have deeply buried active sites, which can be accessed by a substrate via access channels.
[src:enzyme/active-site] There are three proposed models of how enzymes fit their specific substrate: the lock and key model, the induced fit model, and the conformational selection model.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The latter two are not mutually exclusive: conformational selection can be followed by a change in the enzyme's shape.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Additionally, a protein may not wholly follow either model.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Amino acids at the binding site of ubiquitin generally follow the induced fit model, whereas the rest of the protein generally adheres to conformational selection.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Factors such as temperature likely influences the pathway taken during binding, with higher temperatures predicted to increase the importance of conformational selection and decrease that of induced fit.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This concept was suggested by the 19th-century chemist Emil Fischer.
[src:enzyme/active-site] He proposed that the active site and substrate are two stable structures that fit perfectly without any further modification, just like a key fits into a lock.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If one substrate perfectly binds to its active site, the interactions between them will be strongest, resulting in high catalytic efficiency.
[src:enzyme/active-site] As time went by, limitations of this model started to appear.
[src:enzyme/active-site] For example, the competitive enzyme inhibitor methylglucoside can bind tightly to the active site of 4-alpha-glucanotransferase and perfectly fits into it.
[src:enzyme/active-site] However, 4-alpha-glucanotransferase is not active on methylglucoside and no glycosyl transfer occurs.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The Lock and Key hypothesis cannot explain this, as it would predict a high efficiency of methylglucoside glycosyl transfer due to its tight binding.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Apart from competitive inhibition, this theory cannot explain the mechanism of action of non-competitive inhibitors either, as they do not bind to the active site but nevertheless influence catalytic activity.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Daniel Koshland's theory of enzyme-substrate binding is that the active site and the binding portion of the substrate are not exactly complementary.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The induced fit model is a development of the lock-and-key model and assumes that an active site is flexible and changes shape until the substrate is completely bound.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This model is similar to a person wearing a glove: the glove changes shape to fit the hand.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The enzyme initially has a conformation that attracts its substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Enzyme surface is flexible and only the correct catalyst can induce interaction leading to catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Conformational changes may then occur as the substrate is bound.
[src:enzyme/active-site] After the reaction products will move away from the enzyme and the active site returns to its initial shape.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This hypothesis is supported by the observation that the entire protein domain could move several nanometers during catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This movement of protein surface can create microenvironments that favour the catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This model suggests that enzymes exist in a variety of conformations, only some of which are capable of binding to a substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] When a substrate is bound to the protein, the equilibrium in the conformational ensemble shifts towards those able to bind ligands (as enzymes with bound substrates are removed from the equilibrium between the free conformations).
[src:enzyme/active-site] Positively charged sodium ion and negatively charged fluoride ion attract each other to form sodium fluoride under electrostatic interaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Hydrogen bond between two water molecules.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Van der Waals force between two acetone molecules.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The lower acetone molecule contains a partially negative oxygen atom that attracts partially positive carbon atom in the upper acetone.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Hydrophobic and hydrophilic groups tend to assemble with the same kind of molecules.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Once the substrate is bound and oriented to the active site, catalysis can begin.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The residues of the catalytic site are typically very close to the binding site, and some residues can have dual-roles in both binding and catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] During enzyme catalytic reaction, the substrate and active site are brought together in a close proximity.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Firstly, when substrates bind within the active site the effective concentration of it significantly increases than in solution.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This means the number of substrate molecules involved in the reaction is also increased.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This process also reduces the desolvation energy required for the reaction to occur.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In solution substrate molecules are surrounded by solvent molecules and energy is required for enzyme molecules to replace them and contact with the substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Since bulk molecules can be excluded from the active site this energy output can be minimised.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Next, the active site is designed to reorient the substrate to reduce the activation energy for the reaction to occur.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The alignment of the substrate, after binding, is locked in a high energy state and can proceed to the next step.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In addition, this binding is favoured by entropy as the energy cost associated with solution reaction is largely eliminated since solvent cannot enter active site.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In the end, the active site may manipulate the Molecular orbital of the substrate into a suitable orientation to reduce activation energy.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The electrostatic states of substrate and active site must be complementary to each other.
[src:enzyme/active-site] A polarized negatively charged amino acid side chain will repel uncharged substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] But if the transition state involves the formation of an ion centre then the side chain will now produce a favourable interaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Many enzymes including serine protease, cysteine protease, protein kinase and phosphatase evolved to form transient covalent bonds between them and their substrates to lower the activation energy and allow the reaction to occur.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This process can be divided into 2 steps: formation and breakdown.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The former step is rate-limit step while the later step is needed to regenerate intact enzyme.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Metal ions have multiple roles during the reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Firstly it can bind to negatively charged substrate groups so they will not repel electron pairs from active site's nucleophilic groups.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It can attract negatively charged electrons to increase electrophilicity.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It can also bridge between active site and substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] At last, they may change the conformational structure of the substrate to favour reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In some reactions, protons and hydroxide may directly act as acid and base in term of specific acid and specific base catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] But more often groups in substrate and active site act as Brønsted–Lowry acid and base.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This is called general acid and general base theory.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The easiest way to distinguish between them is to check whether the reaction rate is determined by the concentrations of the general acid and base.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If the answer is yes then the reaction is the general type.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Since most enzymes have an optimum pH of 6 to 7, the amino acids in the side chain usually have a p*K*a of 4~10.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Candidate include aspartate, glutamate, histidine, cysteine.
[src:enzyme/active-site] These acids and bases can stabilise the nucleophile or electrophile formed during the catalysis by providing positive and negative charges.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Quantitative studies of enzymatic reactions often found that the acceleration of chemical reaction speed cannot be fully explained by existing theories like the approximation, acid/base catalysis and electrophile/nucleophile catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] And there is an obvious paradox: in reversible enzymatic reaction if the active site perfectly fits the substrates then the backward reaction will be slowed since products cannot fit perfectly into the active site.
[src:enzyme/active-site] So conformational distortion was introduced and argues that both active site and substrate can undergo conformational changes to fit with each other all the time.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This theory is a little similar to the Lock and Key Theory, but at this time the active site is preprogrammed to bind perfectly to substrate in transition state rather than in ground state.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The formation of transition state within the solution requires a large amount of energy to relocate solvent molecules and the reaction is slowed.
[src:enzyme/active-site] So the active site can substitute solvent molecules and surround the substrates to minimize the counterproductive effect imposed by the solution.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The presence of charged groups with the active site will attract substrates and ensure electrostatic complementarity.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In reality, most enzyme mechanisms involve a combination of several different types of catalysis.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The role of glutathione(GSH) is to remove accumulated reactive oxygen species which may damage cells.
[src:enzyme/active-site] During this process, its thiol side chain is oxidised and two glutathione molecules are connected by a disulphide bond to form a dimer(GSSG).
[src:enzyme/active-site] In order to regenerate glutathione the disulphide bond has to be broken, In human cells, this is done by glutathione reductase(GR).
[src:enzyme/active-site] Glutathione reductase is a dimer that contains two identical subunits.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It requires one NADP and one FAD as the cofactors.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The active site is located in the linkage between two subunits.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The NADPH is involved in the generation of FADH-.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In the active site, there are two cysteine residues besides the FAD cofactor and are used to break the disulphide bond during the catalytic reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] NADPH is bound by three positively charged residues: Arg-218, His-219 and Arg-224.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The catalytic process starts when the FAD is reduced by NADPH to accept one electron and from FADH−.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It then attacks the disulphide bond formed between 2 cysteine residues, forming one SH bond and a single S− group.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This S− group will act as a nucleophile to attack the disulphide bond in the oxidised glutathione(GSSG), breaking it and forming a cysteine-SG complex.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The first SG− anion is released and then receives one proton from adjacent SH group and from the first glutathione monomer.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Next the adjacent S− group attack disulphide bond in cysteine-SG complex and release the second SG− anion.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It receives one proton in solution and forms the second glutathione monomer.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Chymotrypsin is a serine endopeptidase that is present in pancreatic juice and helps the hydrolysis of proteins and peptide.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It catalyzes the hydrolysis of peptide bonds in L-isomers of tyrosine, phenylalanine, and tryptophan.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In the active site of this enzyme, three amino acid residues work together to form a catalytic triad which makes up the catalytic site.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In chymotrypsin, these residues are Ser-195, His-57 and Asp-102.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The mechanism of chymotrypsin can be divided into two phases.
[src:enzyme/active-site] First, Ser-195 nucleophilically attacks the peptide bond carbon in the substrate to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The nucleophilicity of Ser-195 is enhanced by His-57, which abstracts a proton from Ser-195 and is in turn stabilised by the negatively charged carboxylate group (RCOO−) in Asp-102.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Furthermore, the tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate generated in this step is stabilised by hydrogen bonds from Ser-195 and Gly-193.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In the second stage, the R'NH group is protonated by His-57 to form R'NH2 and leaves the intermediate, leaving behind the acylated Ser-195.
[src:enzyme/active-site] His-57 then acts as a base again to abstract one proton from a water molecule.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The resulting hydroxide anion nucleophilically attacks the acyl-enzyme complex to form a second tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate, which is once again stabilised by H bonds.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In the end, Ser-195 leaves the tetrahedral intermediate, breaking the CO bond that connected the enzyme to the peptide substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] A proton is transferred to Ser-195 through His-57, so that all three amino acid return to their initial state.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Substrate unbinding is influenced by various factors.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Larger ligands generally stay in the active site longer, as do those with more rotatable bonds (although this may be a side effect of size).
[src:enzyme/active-site] When the solvent is excluded from the active site, less flexible proteins result in longer residence times.
[src:enzyme/active-site] More hydrogen bonds shielded from the solvent also decrease unbinding.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Enzymes can use cofactors as 'helper molecules'.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Coenzymes are referred to those non-protein molecules that bind with enzymes to help them fulfill their jobs.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Mostly they are connected to the active site by non-covalent bonds such as hydrogen bond or hydrophobic interaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] But sometimes a covalent bond can also form between them.
[src:enzyme/active-site] For example, the heme in cytochrome C is bound to the protein through thioester bond.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In some occasions, coenzymes can leave enzymes after the reaction is finished.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Otherwise, they permanently bind to the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Coenzyme is a broad concept which includes metal ions, various vitamins and ATP.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If an enzyme needs coenzyme to work itself, it is called an apoenzyme.
[src:enzyme/active-site] In fact, it alone cannot catalyze reactions properly.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Only when its cofactor comes in and binds to the active site to form holoenzyme does it work properly.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It contains a distinct conjugated isoalloxazine ring system.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Flavin has multiple redox states and can be used in processes that involve the transfer of one or two electrons.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It can act as an electron acceptor in reaction, like the oxidation of NAD to NADH, to accept two electrons and form 1,5-dihydroflavin.
[src:enzyme/active-site] On the other hand, it can form semiquinone(free radical) by accepting one electron, and then converts to fully reduced form by the addition of an extra electron.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This property allows it to be used in one electron oxidation process.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Inhibitors disrupt the interaction between enzyme and substrate, slowing down the rate of a reaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] There are different types of inhibitor, including both reversible and irreversible forms.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Competitive inhibitors are inhibitors that only target free enzyme molecules.
[src:enzyme/active-site] They compete with substrates for free enzyme acceptor and can be overcome by increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Competitive inhibitors usually have structural similarities to the substrates and or ES complex.
[src:enzyme/active-site] As a result, they can fit into the active site and trigger favourable interactions to fill in the space and block substrates from entry.
[src:enzyme/active-site] They can also induce transient conformational changes in the active site so substrates cannot fit perfectly with it.
[src:enzyme/active-site] After a short period of time, competitive inhibitors will drop off and leave the enzyme intact.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Inhibitors are classified as non-competitive inhibitors when they bind both free enzyme and ES complex.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Since they do not compete with substrates for the active site, they cannot be overcome by simply increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme/active-site] They usually bind to a different site on the enzyme and alter the 3-dimensional structure of the active site to block substrates from entry or leaving the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Irreversible inhibitors are similar to competitive inhibitors as they both bind to the active site.
[src:enzyme/active-site] However, irreversible inhibitors form irreversible covalent bonds with the amino acid residues in the active site and never leave.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Therefore, the active site is occupied and the substrate cannot enter.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Occasionally the inhibitor will leave but the catalytic site is permanently altered in shape.
[src:enzyme/active-site] These inhibitors usually contain electrophilic groups like halogen substitutes and epoxides.
[src:enzyme/active-site] As time goes by more and more enzymes are bound by irreversible inhibitors and cannot function anymore.
[src:enzyme/active-site] HIV protease inhibitors are used to treat patients having AIDS virus by preventing its DNA replication.
[src:enzyme/active-site] HIV protease is used by the virus to cleave Gag-Pol polyprotein into 3 smaller proteins that are responsible for virion assembly, package and maturation.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This enzyme targets the specific phenylalanine-proline cleave site within the target protein.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If HIV protease is switched off the virion particle will lose function and cannot infect patients.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Since it is essential in viral replication and is absent in healthy human, it is an ideal target for drug development.
[src:enzyme/active-site] HIV protease belongs to aspartic protease family and has a similar mechanism.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Firstly the aspartate residue activates a water molecule and turns it into a nucleophile.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Then it attacks the carbonyl group within the peptide bond (NH-CO) to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The nitrogen atom within the intermediate receives a proton, forming an amide group and subsequent rearrangement leads to the breakdown of the bond between it and the intermediate and forms two products.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Inhibitors usually contain a nonhydrolyzable hydroxyethylene or hydroxyethylamine groups that mimic the tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Since they share a similar structure and electrostatic arrangement to the transition state of substrates they can still fit into the active site but cannot be broken down, so hydrolysis cannot occur.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Strychnine is a neurotoxin that causes death by affecting nerves that control muscular contraction and cause respiration difficulty.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The impulse is transmitted between the synapse through a neurotransmitter called acetylcholine.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It is released into the synapse between nerve cells and binds to receptors in the postsynaptic cell.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Then an action potential is generated and transmitted through the postsynaptic cell to start a new cycle.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Glycine can inhibit the activity of neurotransmitter receptors, thus a larger amount of acetylcholinesterase is required to trigger an action potential.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This makes sure that the generation of nerve impulses is tightly controlled.
[src:enzyme/active-site] However, this control is broken down when strychnine is added.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It inhibits glycine receptors(a chloride channel) and a much lower level of neurotransmitter concentration can trigger an action potential.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Nerves now constantly transmit signals and cause excessive muscular contraction, leading to asphyxiation and death.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Diisopropyl fluorophosphate (DIFP) is an irreversible inhibitor that blocks the action of serine protease.
[src:enzyme/active-site] When it binds to the enzyme a nucleophilic substitution reaction occurs and releases one hydrogen fluoride molecule.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The OH group in the active site acts as a nucleophile to attack the phosphorus in DIFP and form a tetrahedral intermediate and release a proton.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Then the P-F bond is broken, one electron is transferred to the F atom and it leaves the intermediate as F− anion.
[src:enzyme/active-site] It combines with a proton in solution to form one HF molecule.
[src:enzyme/active-site] A covalent bond formed between the active site and DIFP, so the serine side chain is no longer available to the substrate.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Identification of active sites is crucial in the process of drug discovery.
[src:enzyme/active-site] The 3-D structure of the enzyme is analysed to identify active site residues and design drugs which can fit into them.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Proteolytic enzymes are targets for some drugs, such as protease inhibitors, which include drugs against AIDS and hypertension.
[src:enzyme/active-site] These protease inhibitors bind to an enzyme's active site and block interaction with natural substrates.
[src:enzyme/active-site] An important factor in drug design is the strength of binding between the active site and an enzyme inhibitor.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If the enzyme found in bacteria is significantly different from the human enzyme then an inhibitor can be designed against that particular bacterium without harming the human enzyme.
[src:enzyme/active-site] If one kind of enzyme is only present in one kind of organism, its inhibitor can be used to specifically wipe them out.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Active sites can be mapped to aid the design of new drugs such as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This involves the description of the size of an active site and the number and properties of sub-sites, such as details of the binding interaction.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Modern database technology called CPASS (Comparison of Protein Active Site Structures) however allows the comparison of active sites in more detail and the finding of structural similarity using software.
[src:enzyme/active-site] An allosteric site is a site on an enzyme, unrelated to its active site, which can bind an effector molecule.
[src:enzyme/active-site] This interaction is another mechanism of enzyme regulation.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Allosteric modification usually happens in proteins with more than one subunit.
[src:enzyme/active-site] Allosteric interactions are often present in metabolic pathways and are beneficial in that they allow one step of a reaction to regulate another step.
[src:enzyme/active-site] They allow an enzyme to have a range of molecular interactions, other than the highly specific active site.
[src:enzyme/ase] The suffix **-ase** is used in biochemistry to form names of enzymes.
[src:enzyme/ase] The most common way to name enzymes is to add this suffix onto the end of the substrate, *e.g.* an enzyme that breaks down peroxides may be called peroxidase; the enzyme that produces telomeres is called telomerase.
[src:enzyme/ase] Sometimes enzymes are named for the function they perform, rather than substrate, e.g. the enzyme that polymerizes (assembles) DNA into strands is called polymerase; see also reverse transcriptase.
[src:enzyme/ase] The *-ase* suffix is a libfix derived from "diastase", the first recognized enzyme.
[src:enzyme/ase] Its usage in subsequently discovered enzymes was proposed by Émile Duclaux, with the intention of honoring the first scientists to isolate diastase.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Some such enzymes are integral membrane proteins (anchored within biological membranes), and move solutes across the membrane, typically against their concentration gradient.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Transmembrane ATPases import metabolites necessary for cell metabolism and export toxins, wastes, and solutes that can hinder cellular processes.
[src:enzyme/atpase] An important example is the sodium-potassium pump (Na+/K+ATPase) that maintains the cell membrane potential.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Another example is the hydrogen potassium ATPase (H+/K+ATPase or gastric proton pump) that acidifies the contents of the stomach.
[src:enzyme/atpase] ATPase is genetically conserved in animals; therefore, cardenolides which are toxic steroids produced by plants that act on ATPases, make general and effective animal toxins that act dose dependently.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Besides exchangers, other categories of transmembrane ATPase include co-transporters and pumps (however, some exchangers are also pumps).
[src:enzyme/atpase] Some of these, like the Na+/K+ATPase, cause a net flow of charge, but others do not.
[src:enzyme/atpase] These are called electrogenic transporters and electroneutral transporters, respectively.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Genetic variants in ATPases result in a wide spectrum of human diseases, from prenatal to later onset disease.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The Walker motifs are a telltale protein sequence motif for nucleotide binding and hydrolysis.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Beyond this broad function, the Walker motifs can be found in almost all natural ATPases, with the notable exception of tyrosine kinases.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The Walker motifs commonly form a Beta sheet-turn-Alpha helix that is self-organized as a Nest (protein structural motif).
[src:enzyme/atpase] This is thought to be because modern ATPases evolved from small NTP-binding peptides that had to be self-organized.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Protein design has been able to replicate the ATPase function (weakly) without using natural ATPase sequences or structures.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Importantly, while all natural ATPases have some beta-sheet structure, the designed "Alternative ATPase" lacks beta sheet structure, demonstrating that this life-essential function is possible with sequences and structures not found in nature.
[src:enzyme/atpase] ATPase (also called FoF1-ATP Synthase) is a charge-transferring complex that catalyzes ATP to perform ATP synthesis by moving ions through the membrane.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The coupling of ATP hydrolysis and transport is a chemical reaction in which a fixed number of solute molecules are transported for each ATP molecule hydrolyzed; for the Na+/K+ exchanger, this is three Na+ ions out of the cell and two K+ ions inside per ATP molecule hydrolyzed.
[src:enzyme/atpase] This process is referred to as active transport.
[src:enzyme/atpase] For instance, inhibiting vesicular H+-ATPases would result in a rise in the pH within vesicles and a drop in the pH of the cytoplasm.
[src:enzyme/atpase] All of the ATPases share a common basic structure.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Each rotary ATPase is composed of two major components: Fo/A0/V0 and F1/A1/V1.
[src:enzyme/atpase] They are connected by 1-3 stalks to maintain stability, control rotation, and prevent them from rotating in the other direction.
[src:enzyme/atpase] One stalk is utilized to transmit torque.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The number of peripheral stalks is dependent on the type of ATPase: F-ATPases have one, A-ATPases have two, and V-ATPases have three.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The F1 catalytic domain is located on the N-side (negative-side) of the membrane and is involved in the synthesis and degradation of ATP and is involved in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The Fo transmembrane domain is involved in the movement of ions across the membrane.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The bacterial FoF1-ATPase consists of the soluble F1 domain and the transmembrane Fo domain, which is composed of several subunits with varying stoichiometry.
[src:enzyme/atpase] There are two subunits, γ, and ε, that form the central stalk and they are linked to Fo.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Fo contains a c-subunit oligomer in the shape of a ring (c-ring).
[src:enzyme/atpase] The α subunit is close to the subunit b2 and makes up the stalk that connects the transmembrane subunits to the α3β3 and δ subunits.
[src:enzyme/atpase] F-ATP synthases are identical in appearance and function except for the mitochondrial FoF1-ATP synthase, which contains 7-9 additional subunits.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The electrochemical potential is what causes the c-ring to rotate in a clockwise direction for ATP synthesis.
[src:enzyme/atpase] This causes the central stalk and the catalytic domain to change shape.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Rotating the c-ring causes three ATP molecules to be made, which then causes H+ to move from the P-side (positive-side) of the membrane to the N-side (negative-side) of the membrane.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The counterclockwise rotation of the c-ring is driven by ATP hydrolysis and ions move from the N-side to the P-side, which helps to build up electrochemical potential.
[src:enzyme/atpase] The ATP synthase of mitochondria and chloroplasts is an anabolic enzyme that harnesses the energy of a transmembrane proton gradient as an energy source for adding an inorganic phosphate group to a molecule of adenosine diphosphate (ADP) to form a molecule of adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:enzyme/atpase] This enzyme works when a proton moves down the concentration gradient, giving the enzyme a spinning motion.
[src:enzyme/atpase] This unique spinning motion bonds ADP and P together to create ATP.
[src:enzyme/atpase] ATP synthase can also function in reverse, that is, use energy released by ATP hydrolysis to pump protons against their electrochemical gradient.
[src:enzyme/atpase] There are different types of ATPases, which can differ in function (ATP synthesis and/or hydrolysis), structure (F-, V- and A-ATPases contain rotary motors) and in the type of ions they transport.
[src:enzyme/atpase] P-ATPases (sometime known as E1-E2 ATPases) are found in bacteria and also in eukaryotic plasma membranes and organelles.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Its name is due to short time attachment of inorganic phosphate at the aspartate residues at the time of activation.
[src:enzyme/atpase] Function of P-ATPase is to transport a variety of different compounds, like ions and phospholipids, across a membrane using ATP hydrolysis for energy.
[src:enzyme/atpase] There are many different classes of P-ATPases, which transports a specific type of ion.
[src:enzyme/atpase] P-ATPases may be composed of one or two polypeptides, and can usually take two main conformations, E1 and E2.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An **enzyme** is a biological macromolecule, usually a protein, that acts as a biological catalyst, accelerating chemical reactions without being consumed in the process.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The molecules on which enzymes act are called substrates, which are converted into products.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Nearly all metabolic processes within a cell depend on enzyme catalysis to occur at biologically relevant rates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A metabolic pathway is typically composed of a series of enzyme-catalyzed steps.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The study of enzymes is known as *enzymology*, and a related field focuses on pseudoenzymes—proteins that have lost catalytic activity but may retain regulatory or scaffolding functions, often indicated by alterations in their amino acid sequences or unusual 'pseudocatalytic' behavior.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes are known to catalyze over 5,000 types of biochemical reactions.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Other biological catalysts include catalytic RNA molecules, or ribozymes, which are sometimes classified as enzymes despite being composed of RNA rather than protein.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] More recently, biomolecular condensates have been recognized as a third category of biocatalysts, capable of catalyzing reactions by creating interfaces and gradients—such as ionic gradients—that drive biochemical processes, even when their component proteins are not intrinsically catalytic.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes increase the reaction rate by lowering a reaction's activation energy, often by factors of millions.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A striking example is orotidine 5′-phosphate decarboxylase, which accelerates a reaction that would otherwise take millions of years to occur in milliseconds.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Like all catalysts, enzymes do not affect the overall equilibrium of a reaction and are regenerated at the end of each cycle.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] What distinguishes them is their high specificity, determined by their unique three-dimensional structure, and their sensitivity to factors such as temperature and pH.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme activity can be enhanced by activators or diminished by inhibitors, many of which serve as drugs or poisons.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Outside optimal conditions, enzymes may lose their structure through denaturation, leading to loss of function.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes have widespread practical applications.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In industry, they are used to catalyze the production of antibiotics and other complex molecules.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In everyday life, enzymes in biological washing powders break down protein, starch, and fat stains, enhancing cleaning performance.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Papain and other proteolytic enzymes are used in meat tenderizers to hydrolyze proteins, improving texture and digestibility.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Their specificity and efficiency make enzymes indispensable in both biological systems and commercial processes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] By the late 17th and early 18th centuries, the digestion of meat by stomach secretions and the conversion of starch to sugars by plant extracts and saliva were known but the mechanisms by which these occurred had not been identified.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] French chemist Anselme Payen was the first to discover an enzyme, diastase, in 1833.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A few decades later, when studying the fermentation of sugar to alcohol by yeast, Louis Pasteur concluded that this fermentation was caused by a vital force contained within the yeast cells called "ferments", which were thought to function only within living organisms.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In 1877, German physiologist Wilhelm Kühne (1837–1900) first used the term *enzyme*, which comes from Ancient Greek ἔνζυμον*(énzymon)* 'leavened, in yeast', to describe this process.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The word *enzyme* was used later to refer to nonliving substances such as pepsin, and the word *ferment* was used to refer to chemical activity produced by living organisms.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Eduard Buchner submitted his first paper on the study of yeast extracts in 1897.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In a series of experiments at the University of Berlin, he found that sugar was fermented by yeast extracts even when there were no living yeast cells in the mixture.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] He named the enzyme that brought about the fermentation of sucrose "zymase".
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In 1907, he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for "his discovery of cell-free fermentation".
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Following Buchner's example, enzymes are usually named according to the reaction they carry out: the suffix *-ase* is combined with the name of the substrate (e.g., lactase is the enzyme that cleaves lactose) or to the type of reaction (e.g., DNA polymerase forms DNA polymers).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The biochemical identity of enzymes was still unknown in the early 1900s.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Many scientists observed that enzymatic activity was associated with proteins, but others (such as Nobel laureate Richard Willstätter) argued that proteins were merely carriers for the true enzymes and that proteins *per se* were incapable of catalysis.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Sumner showed that the enzyme urease was a pure protein and crystallized it; he did likewise for the enzyme catalase in 1937.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The conclusion that pure proteins can be enzymes was definitively demonstrated by John Howard Northrop and Wendell Meredith Stanley, who worked on the digestive enzymes pepsin (1930), trypsin and chymotrypsin.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These three scientists were awarded the 1946 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The discovery that enzymes could be crystallized eventually allowed their structures to be solved by x-ray crystallography.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This was first done for lysozyme, an enzyme found in tears, saliva and egg whites that digests the coating of some bacteria; the structure was solved by a group led by David Chilton Phillips and published in 1965.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This high-resolution structure of lysozyme marked the beginning of the field of structural biology and the effort to understand how enzymes work at an atomic level of detail.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes can be classified by two main criteria: either their enzymatic activity or their amino acid sequence similarity (and thus evolutionary relationship).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An enzyme's name is often derived from its substrate or the chemical reaction it catalyzes, with the word ending in *-ase*.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Examples are lactase, alcohol dehydrogenase and DNA polymerase.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Different enzymes that catalyze the same chemical reaction are called isozymes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology have developed a nomenclature for enzymes, the EC numbers (for "Enzyme Commission").
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Each enzyme is described by "EC" followed by a sequence of four numbers which represent the hierarchy of enzymatic activity (from very general to very specific).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] That is, the first number broadly classifies the enzyme based on its mechanism while the other digits add more and more specificity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These sections are subdivided by other features such as the substrate, products, and chemical mechanism.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An enzyme is fully specified by four numerical designations.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, hexokinase (EC 2.7.1.1) is a transferase (EC 2) that adds a phosphate group (EC 2.7) to a hexose sugar, a molecule containing an alcohol group (EC 2.7.1).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] EC categories do not reflect sequence similarity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For instance, two ligases of the same EC number that catalyze exactly the same reaction can have completely different sequences.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Independent of their function, enzymes, like any other proteins, have been classified by their sequence similarity into numerous families.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These families have been documented in dozens of different protein and protein family databases such as Pfam.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Unrelated enzymes that have the same enzymatic activity have been called *non-homologous isofunctional enzymes*.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Horizontal gene transfer may spread these genes to unrelated species, especially bacteria where they can replace endogenous genes of the same function, leading to hon-homologous gene displacement.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes are generally globular proteins, acting alone or in larger complexes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The sequence of the amino acids specifies the structure which in turn determines the catalytic activity of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Although structure determines function, a novel enzymatic activity cannot yet be predicted from structure alone.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme structures unfold (denature) when heated or exposed to chemical denaturants and this disruption to the structure typically causes a loss of activity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes are usually much larger than their substrates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Sizes range from just 62 amino acid residues, for the monomer of 4-oxalocrotonate tautomerase, to over 2,500 residues in the animal fatty acid synthase.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Only a small portion of their structure (around 2–4 amino acids) is directly involved in catalysis: the catalytic site.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This catalytic site is located next to one or more binding sites where residues orient the substrates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The catalytic site and binding site together compose the enzyme's active site.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The remaining majority of the enzyme structure serves to maintain the precise orientation and dynamics of the active site.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In some enzymes, no amino acids are directly involved in catalysis; instead, the enzyme contains sites to bind and orient catalytic cofactors.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme structures may also contain allosteric sites where the binding of a small molecule causes a conformational change that increases or decreases activity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A small number of RNA-based biological catalysts called ribozymes exist, which again can act alone or in complex with proteins.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The most common of these is the ribosome which is a complex of protein and catalytic RNA components.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes must bind their substrates before they can catalyze any chemical reaction.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes are usually very specific as to what substrates they bind and then the chemical reaction catalyzed.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Specificity is achieved by binding pockets with complementary shape, charge and hydrophilic/hydrophobic characteristics to the substrates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes can therefore distinguish between very similar substrate molecules to be chemoselective, regioselective and stereospecific.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Some of the enzymes showing the highest specificity and accuracy are involved in the copying and expression of the genome.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Some of these enzymes have "proof-reading" mechanisms.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Here, an enzyme such as DNA polymerase catalyzes a reaction in a first step and then checks that the product is correct in a second step.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This two-step process results in average error rates of less than 1 error in 100 million reactions in high-fidelity mammalian polymerases.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Similar proofreading mechanisms are also found in RNA polymerase, aminoacyl tRNA synthetases and ribosomes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Conversely, some enzymes display enzyme promiscuity, having broad specificity and acting on a range of different physiologically relevant substrates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Many enzymes possess small side activities which arose fortuitously (i.e. neutrally), which may be the starting point for the evolutionary selection of a new function.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] To explain the observed specificity of enzymes, in 1894 Emil Fischer proposed that both the enzyme and the substrate possess specific complementary geometric shapes that fit exactly into one another.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This is often referred to as "the lock and key" model.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This early model explains enzyme specificity, but fails to explain the stabilization of the transition state that enzymes achieve.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In 1958, Daniel Koshland suggested a modification to the lock and key model: since enzymes are rather flexible structures, the active site is continuously reshaped by interactions with the substrate as the substrate interacts with the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] As a result, the substrate does not simply bind to a rigid active site; the amino acid side-chains that make up the active site are molded into the precise positions that enable the enzyme to perform its catalytic function.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In some cases, such as glycosidases, the substrate molecule also changes shape slightly as it enters the active site.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The active site continues to change until the substrate is completely bound, at which point the final shape and charge distribution is determined.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Induced fit may enhance the fidelity of molecular recognition in the presence of competition and noise via the conformational proofreading mechanism.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes may use several of these mechanisms simultaneously.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, proteases such as trypsin perform covalent catalysis using a catalytic triad, stabilize charge build-up on the transition states using an oxyanion hole, complete hydrolysis using an oriented water substrate.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes are not rigid, static structures; instead they have complex internal dynamic motions – that is, movements of parts of the enzyme's structure such as individual amino acid residues, groups of residues forming a protein loop or unit of secondary structure, or even an entire protein domain.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These motions give rise to a conformational ensemble of slightly different structures that interconvert with one another at equilibrium.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Different states within this ensemble may be associated with different aspects of an enzyme's function.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, different conformations of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase are associated with the substrate binding, catalysis, cofactor release, and product release steps of the catalytic cycle, consistent with catalytic resonance theory.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The transitions between the different conformations during the catalytic cycle involve internal viscoelastic motion that is facilitated by high-strain regions where amino acids are rearranged.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Substrate presentation is a process where the enzyme is sequestered away from its substrate.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes can be sequestered to the plasma membrane away from a substrate in the nucleus or cytosol.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Or within the membrane, an enzyme can be sequestered into lipid rafts away from its substrate in the disordered region.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] When the enzyme is released it mixes with its substrate.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Alternatively, the enzyme can be sequestered near its substrate to activate the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, the enzyme can be soluble and upon activation bind to a lipid in the plasma membrane and then act upon molecules in the plasma membrane.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Allosteric sites are pockets on the enzyme, distinct from the active site, that bind to molecules in the cellular environment.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These molecules then cause a change in the conformation or dynamics of the enzyme that is transduced to the active site and thus affects the reaction rate of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In this way, allosteric interactions can either inhibit or activate enzymes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Allosteric interactions with metabolites upstream or downstream in an enzyme's metabolic pathway cause feedback regulation, altering the activity of the enzyme according to the flux through the rest of the pathway.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Some enzymes do not need additional components to show full activity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Others require non-protein molecules called cofactors to be bound for activity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Cofactors can be either inorganic (e.g., metal ions and iron–sulfur clusters) or organic compounds (e.g., flavin and heme).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These cofactors serve many purposes; for instance, metal ions can help in stabilizing nucleophilic species within the active site.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Organic cofactors can be either coenzymes, which are released from the enzyme's active site during the reaction, or prosthetic groups, which are tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Organic prosthetic groups can be covalently bound (e.g., biotin in enzymes such as pyruvate carboxylase).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An example of an enzyme that contains a cofactor is carbonic anhydrase, which uses a zinc cofactor bound as part of its active site.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These tightly bound ions or molecules are usually found in the active site and are involved in catalysis.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, flavin and heme cofactors are often involved in redox reactions.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes that require a cofactor but do not have one bound are called *apoenzymes* or *apoproteins*.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An enzyme together with the cofactor(s) required for activity is called a *holoenzyme* (or haloenzyme).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The term *holoenzyme* can also be applied to enzymes that contain multiple protein subunits, such as the DNA polymerases; here the holoenzyme is the complete complex containing all the subunits needed for activity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Coenzymes are small organic molecules that can be loosely or tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Coenzymes transport chemical groups from one enzyme to another.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Examples include NADH, NADPH and adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Some coenzymes, such as flavin mononucleotide (FMN), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), and tetrahydrofolate (THF), are derived from vitamins.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These coenzymes cannot be synthesized by the body *de novo* and closely related compounds (vitamins) must be acquired from the diet.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Since coenzymes are chemically changed as a consequence of enzyme action, it is useful to consider coenzymes to be a special class of substrates, or second substrates, which are common to many different enzymes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, about 1000 enzymes are known to use the coenzyme NADH.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Coenzymes are usually continuously regenerated and their concentrations maintained at a steady level inside the cell.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, NADPH is regenerated through the pentose phosphate pathway and *S*-adenosylmethionine by methionine adenosyltransferase.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This continuous regeneration means that small amounts of coenzymes can be used very intensively.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, the human body turns over its own weight in ATP each day.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] As with all catalysts, enzymes do not alter the position of the chemical equilibrium of the reaction.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In the presence of an enzyme, the reaction runs in the same direction as it would without the enzyme, just more quickly.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The rate of a reaction is dependent on the activation energy needed to form the transition state which then decays into products.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes increase reaction rates by lowering the energy of the transition state.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] First, binding forms a low energy enzyme-substrate complex (ES).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Second, the enzyme stabilises the transition state such that it requires less energy to achieve compared to the uncatalyzed reaction (ES‡).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Finally the enzyme-product complex (EP) dissociates to release the products.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes can couple two or more reactions, so that a thermodynamically favorable reaction can be used to "drive" a thermodynamically unfavourable one so that the combined energy of the products is lower than the substrates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, the hydrolysis of ATP is often used to drive other chemical reactions.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] for an enzyme reaction showing the relation between the substrate concentration and reaction rate.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme kinetics is the investigation of how enzymes bind substrates and turn them into products.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The rate data used in kinetic analyses are commonly obtained from enzyme assays.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In 1913 Leonor Michaelis and Maud Leonora Menten proposed a quantitative theory of enzyme kinetics, which is referred to as Michaelis–Menten kinetics.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The major contribution of Michaelis and Menten was to think of enzyme reactions in two stages.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In the first, the substrate binds reversibly to the enzyme, forming the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This is sometimes called the Michaelis–Menten complex in their honor.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The enzyme then catalyzes the chemical step in the reaction and releases the product.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Haldane, who derived kinetic equations that are still widely used today.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme rates depend on solution conditions and substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] To find the maximum speed of an enzymatic reaction, the substrate concentration is increased until a constant rate of product formation is seen.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This is shown in the saturation curve on the right.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Saturation happens because, as substrate concentration increases, more and more of the free enzyme is converted into the substrate-bound ES complex.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] At the maximum reaction rate (*V*max) of the enzyme, all the enzyme active sites are bound to substrate, and the amount of ES complex is the same as the total amount of enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The efficiency of an enzyme can be expressed in terms of *k*cat/*K*m.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This is also called the specificity constant and incorporates the rate constants for all steps in the reaction up to and including the first irreversible step.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Because the specificity constant reflects both affinity and catalytic ability, it is useful for comparing different enzymes against each other, or the same enzyme with different substrates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The theoretical maximum for the specificity constant is called the diffusion limit and is about 108 to 109 (M−1 s−1).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] At this point every collision of the enzyme with its substrate will result in catalysis, and the rate of product formation is not limited by the reaction rate but by the diffusion rate.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes with this property are called *catalytically perfect* or *kinetically perfect*.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Example of such enzymes are triose-phosphate isomerase, carbonic anhydrase, acetylcholinesterase, catalase, fumarase, β-lactamase, and superoxide dismutase.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The turnover of such enzymes can reach several million reactions per second.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Michaelis–Menten kinetics relies on the law of mass action, which is derived from the assumptions of free diffusion and thermodynamically driven random collision.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Many biochemical or cellular processes deviate significantly from these conditions, because of macromolecular crowding and constrained molecular movement.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] More recent, complex extensions of the model attempt to correct for these effects.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] (right) are very similar in structure (differences show in green).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] As a result, methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of many enzymes that use folates.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme reaction rates can be decreased by various types of enzyme inhibitors.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A competitive inhibitor and substrate cannot bind to the enzyme at the same time.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Often competitive inhibitors strongly resemble the real substrate of the enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, the drug methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase, which catalyzes the reduction of dihydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The similarity between the structures of dihydrofolate and this drug are shown in the accompanying figure.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This type of inhibition can be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In some cases, the inhibitor can bind to a site other than the binding-site of the usual substrate and exert an allosteric effect to change the shape of the usual binding-site.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A non-competitive inhibitor binds to a site other than where the substrate binds.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The substrate still binds with its usual affinity and hence Km remains the same.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] However the inhibitor reduces the catalytic efficiency of the enzyme so that Vmax is reduced.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In contrast to competitive inhibition, non-competitive inhibition cannot be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An uncompetitive inhibitor cannot bind to the free enzyme, only to the enzyme-substrate complex; hence, these types of inhibitors are most effective at high substrate concentration.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In the presence of the inhibitor, the enzyme-substrate complex is inactive.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A mixed inhibitor binds to an allosteric site and the binding of the substrate and the inhibitor affect each other.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The enzyme's function is reduced but not eliminated when bound to the inhibitor.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This type of inhibitor does not follow the Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An irreversible inhibitor permanently inactivates the enzyme, usually by forming a covalent bond to the protein.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Penicillin and aspirin are common drugs that act in this manner.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In many organisms, inhibitors may act as part of a feedback mechanism.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] If an enzyme produces too much of one substance in the organism, that substance may act as an inhibitor for the enzyme at the beginning of the pathway that produces it, causing production of the substance to slow down or stop when there is sufficient amount.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Major metabolic pathways such as the citric acid cycle make use of this mechanism.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Since inhibitors modulate the function of enzymes they are often used as drugs.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Many such drugs are reversible competitive inhibitors that resemble the enzyme's native substrate, similar to methotrexate above; other well-known examples include statins used to treat high cholesterol, and protease inhibitors used to treat retroviral infections such as HIV.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A common example of an irreversible inhibitor that is used as a drug is aspirin, which inhibits the COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes that produce the inflammation messenger prostaglandin.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, the poison cyanide is an irreversible enzyme inhibitor that combines with the copper and iron in the active site of the enzyme cytochrome c oxidase and blocks cellular respiration.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] As enzymes are made up of proteins, their actions are sensitive to change in many physio chemical factors such as pH, temperature, substrate concentration, etc.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The following table shows pH optima for various enzymes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes serve a wide variety of functions inside living organisms.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] They are indispensable for signal transduction and cell regulation, often via kinases and phosphatases.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] They also generate movement, with myosin hydrolyzing adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to generate muscle contraction, and also transport cargo around the cell as part of the cytoskeleton.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Other ATPases in the cell membrane are ion pumps involved in active transport.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes are also involved in more exotic functions, such as luciferase generating light in fireflies.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Viruses can also contain enzymes for infecting cells, such as the HIV integrase and reverse transcriptase, or for viral release from cells, like the influenza virus neuraminidase.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An important function of enzymes is in the digestive systems of animals.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes such as amylases and proteases break down large molecules (starch or proteins, respectively) into smaller ones, so they can be absorbed by the intestines.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Starch molecules, for example, are too large to be absorbed from the intestine, but enzymes hydrolyze the starch chains into smaller molecules such as maltose and eventually glucose, which can then be absorbed.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Different enzymes digest different food substances.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In ruminants, which have herbivorous diets, microorganisms in the gut produce another enzyme, cellulase, to break down the cellulose cell walls of plant fiber.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Several enzymes can work together in a specific order, creating metabolic pathways.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In a metabolic pathway, one enzyme takes the product of another enzyme as a substrate.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] After the catalytic reaction, the product is then passed on to another enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Sometimes more than one enzyme can catalyze the same reaction in parallel; this can allow more complex regulation: with, for example, a low constant activity provided by one enzyme but an inducible high activity from a second enzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes determine what steps occur in these pathways.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Without enzymes, metabolism would neither progress through the same steps and could not be regulated to serve the needs of the cell.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Most central metabolic pathways are regulated at a few steps, typically through enzymes whose activity involves the phosphorylation by ATP.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Because this reaction releases so much energy, other reactions that are thermodynamically unfavorable can be coupled to ATP hydrolysis, driving the overall series of linked metabolic reactions.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] There are five main ways that enzyme activity is controlled in the cell.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes can be either activated or inhibited by other molecules.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, the end product(s) of a metabolic pathway are often inhibitors for one of the first enzymes of the pathway (usually the first irreversible step, called committed step), thus regulating the amount of end product made by the pathways.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Such a regulatory mechanism is called a negative feedback mechanism, because the amount of the end product produced is regulated by its own concentration.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Negative feedback mechanism can effectively adjust the rate of synthesis of intermediate metabolites according to the demands of the cells.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This helps with effective allocations of materials and energy economy, and it prevents the excess manufacture of end products.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Like other homeostatic devices, the control of enzymatic action helps to maintain a stable internal environment in living organisms.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Examples of post-translational modification include phosphorylation, myristoylation and glycosylation.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, in the response to insulin, the phosphorylation of multiple enzymes, including glycogen synthase, helps control the synthesis or degradation of glycogen and allows the cell to respond to changes in blood sugar.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Another example of post-translational modification is the cleavage of the polypeptide chain.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Chymotrypsin, a digestive protease, is produced in inactive form as chymotrypsinogen in the pancreas and transported in this form to the stomach where it is activated.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This stops the enzyme from digesting the pancreas or other tissues before it enters the gut.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This type of inactive precursor to an enzyme is known as a zymogen or proenzyme.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme production (transcription and translation of enzyme genes) can be enhanced or diminished by a cell in response to changes in the cell's environment.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This form of gene regulation is called enzyme induction.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, bacteria may become resistant to antibiotics such as penicillin because enzymes called beta-lactamases are induced that hydrolyse the crucial beta-lactam ring within the penicillin molecule.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Another example comes from enzymes in the liver called cytochrome P450 oxidases, which are important in drug metabolism.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Induction or inhibition of these enzymes can cause drug interactions.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzyme levels can also be regulated by changing the rate of enzyme degradation.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The opposite of enzyme induction is enzyme repression.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes can be compartmentalized, with different metabolic pathways occurring in different cellular compartments.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, fatty acids are synthesized by one set of enzymes in the cytosol, endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi and used by a different set of enzymes as a source of energy in the mitochondrion, through β-oxidation.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In addition, trafficking of the enzyme to different compartments may change the degree of protonation (e.g., the neutral cytoplasm and the acidic lysosome) or oxidative state (e.g., oxidizing periplasm or reducing cytoplasm) which in turn affects enzyme activity.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In contrast to partitioning into membrane bound organelles, enzyme subcellular localisation may also be altered through polymerisation of enzymes into macromolecular cytoplasmic filaments.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In multicellular eukaryotes, cells in different organs and tissues have different patterns of gene expression and therefore have different sets of enzymes (known as isozymes) available for metabolic reactions.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This provides a mechanism for regulating the overall metabolism of the organism.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] For example, hexokinase, the first enzyme in the glycolysis pathway, has a specialized form called glucokinase expressed in the liver and pancreas that has a lower affinity for glucose yet is more sensitive to glucose concentration.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This enzyme is involved in sensing blood sugar and regulating insulin production.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Since the tight control of enzyme activity is essential for homeostasis, any malfunction (mutation, overproduction, underproduction or deletion) of a single critical enzyme can lead to a genetic disease.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] The malfunction of just one type of enzyme out of the thousands of types present in the human body can be fatal.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An example of a fatal genetic disease due to enzyme insufficiency is Tay–Sachs disease, in which patients lack the enzyme hexosaminidase.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] One example of enzyme deficiency is the most common type of phenylketonuria.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Many different single amino acid mutations in the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, which catalyzes the first step in the degradation of phenylalanine, result in build-up of phenylalanine and related products.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Some mutations are in the active site, directly disrupting binding and catalysis, but many are far from the active site and reduce activity by destabilising the protein structure, or affecting correct oligomerisation.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This can lead to intellectual disability if the disease is untreated.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Another example is pseudocholinesterase deficiency, in which the body's ability to break down choline ester drugs is impaired.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Oral administration of enzymes can be used to treat some functional enzyme deficiencies, such as pancreatic insufficiency and lactose intolerance.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Another way enzyme malfunctions can cause disease comes from germline mutations in genes coding for DNA repair enzymes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Defects in these enzymes cause cancer because cells are less able to repair mutations in their genomes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This causes a slow accumulation of mutations and results in the development of cancers.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] An example of such a hereditary cancer syndrome is xeroderma pigmentosum, which causes the development of skin cancers in response to even minimal exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Similar to any other protein, enzymes change over time through mutations and sequence divergence.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Given their central role in metabolism, enzyme evolution plays a critical role in adaptation.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] A key question is therefore whether and how enzymes can change their enzymatic activities alongside.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] It is generally accepted that many new enzyme activities have evolved through gene duplication and mutation of the duplicate copies although evolution can also happen without duplication.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In addition, MAP is metal-ion dependent while creatinase is not, hence this property was also lost over time.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Small changes of enzymatic activity are extremely common among enzymes.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] In particular, substrate binding specificity (see above) can easily and quickly change with single amino acid changes in their substrate binding pockets.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] This is frequently seen in the main enzyme classes such as kinases.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Artificial (in vitro) evolution is now commonly used to modify enzyme activity or specificity for industrial applications (see below).
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes are used in the chemical industry and other industrial applications when extremely specific catalysts are required.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] Enzymes in general are limited in the number of reactions they have evolved to catalyze and also by their lack of stability in organic solvents and at high temperatures.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] As a consequence, protein engineering is an active area of research and involves attempts to create new enzymes with novel properties, either through rational design or *in vitro* evolution.
[src:enzyme/enzyme] These efforts have begun to be successful, and a few enzymes have now been designed "from scratch" to catalyze reactions that do not occur in nature.
